Greetings! This problem is quite intriguing. Let us delve into it.

Let $O$ be the circumcenter of triangle $ABC.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O, P;

A = dir(110);
B = dir(210);
C = dir(330);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);
P = extension(A, A + dir(110 + 120), B, B + dir(210 + 120));

draw(Circle(O,abs(O - A)));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--P--B);
draw(B--P--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$O$", O, NE);
label("$P$", P, S);
[/asy]

Since $O$ is the circumcenter, $OA = OB = OC = R,$ where $R$ is the circumradius.  Then
\[AB^2 + AP^2 + BP^2 = R^2 + AP^2 + BP^2,\]\[AC^2 + AP^2 + CP^2 = R^2 + AP^2 + CP^2,\]\[BC^2 + BP^2 + CP^2 = R^2 + BP^2 + CP^2.\]Hence,
\[R^2 + AP^2 + BP^2 = R^2 + AP^2 + CP^2 = R^2 + BP^2 + CP^2.\]Therefore, the common value is $R^2 + AP^2 + BP^2.$
